All-loop cuts from the Amplituhedron

Cameron Langer b ‚ÄÉ‚ÄÉ Akshay Yelleshpur Srikant
Abstract

The definition of the amplituhedron in terms of sign flips involves both one-loop constraints and the ‚Äúmutual positivity‚Äù constraint. To gain an understanding of the all-loop integrand of ùí©=4ùí©4\mathcal{N}=4 sYM requires understanding the crucial role played by mutual positivity. This paper is an attempt towards developing a procedure to introduce the complexities of mutual positivity in a systematic and controlled manner. As the first step in this procedure, we trivialize these constraints and understand the geometry underlying the remaining constraints to all loops and multiplicities. We present a host of configurations which correspond to various faces of the amplituhedron. The results we derive are valid at all multiplicities and loop orders for the maximally helicity violating (MHV) configurations. These include detailed derivations for the results in Arkani-Hamed:2018caj . We conclude by indicating how one might move beyond trivial mutual positivity by presenting a series of configuration which re-introduce it bit by bit.

1 Introduction

The amplituhedron is a geometric object that is conjectured to encode all the perturbative scattering amplitudes of planar ùí©=4ùí©4\mathcal{N}=4 sYM. First introduced in TheAmplituhedron , the original definition of this object was built on the discovery of the structures of the positive Grassmannian uncovered in positiveGrass as well as the observation in hodges associating the NMHV tree amplitude to the volume of a particular polytope in momentum twistor space. The amplituhedron realizes a similar geometric picture for general tree amplitudes and loop integrands, associating to each positive geometry a (conjecturally unique) ‚Äúcanonical differential form‚Äù defined by having logarithmic singularities on all its boundaries Arkani-Hamed:2017tmz . The computation of scattering amplitudes in planar ùí©=4ùí©4\mathcal{N}=4 is equivalent to determining a triangulation of the amplituhedron, so that different representations of amplitudes correspond to different geometric triangulations of the space. There is nontrivial evidence Bern:2014kca ; Bern:2015ple ; Bern:2018oao that this geometric construction can be extended to the nonplanar sector of the theory, as the essential analytic properties of the loop integrand, namely logarithmic singularities and no poles at infinity Arkani-Hamed:2014via , have been observed to hold beyond the planar limit.

Understanding this geometry ùíún,k,Lsubscriptùíúùëõùëòùêø\mathcal{A}_{n,k,L} for all multiplicities nùëõn, helicity configurations kùëòk and loop orders LùêøL is an open problem, and many different directions have been explored. The connections between the tree level amplituhedron and the Yangian symmetry of ùí©=4ùí©4\mathcal{N}=4 have been explored in Ferro:2016zmx , while a triangulation-independent understanding of the geometry has been studied from several different perspectives Ferro:2018vpf ; Enciso:2014cta ; Enciso:2016cif , primarily for NMHV trees. An explicit description of how the BCFW cells triangulate the tree-level space was given in Karp:2017ouj while an alternative sign flip reformulation of the m=1ùëö1m=1 amplituhedron was given in Karp:2016uax . A manifestly Yangian invariant diagrammatic formulation using so-called ‚Äúmomentum twistor diagrams‚Äù was introduced in Bai:2014cna and used to study the structure of the one-loop geometry in Bai:2015qoa . The higher loop-level geometry of the amplituhedron was explored in detail in IntoTheAmplituhedron ; Anatomy and an attempt to completely understand the geometry at four points and progressively higher loops can be found in 4pt1 ; 4pt2 ; 4pt3 . However, important open questions regarding the technical details of triangulating the amplituhedron remain. Moreover, while the original definition provided a deeper understanding of the positive Grassmannian and on-shell diagrammatic structure of scattering amplitudes in ùí©=4ùí©4\mathcal{N}=4 sYM, it was still slightly unsatisfactory since all these structures were associated to an auxiliary space not directly tied to the kinematic data.

The introduction of the topological definition of the amplituhedron in Arkani-Hamed:2017vfh completely resolved this issue, revealing the geometric structure of the amplitudes directly in kinematic space. In this new formulation, the amplitudes and loop integrands could now be thought of as differential forms in momentum twistor space depending on the loop integration variables as well as the external data. Recently, it was discovered that the scattering amplitudes in other theories may also be written as differential forms on the space of kinematical data, see e.g, notesdiff ; associahedron ; halohedron1 .

The topological definition also makes it clear that the inequalities that define the multi-loop amplituhedron fall into two categories. The first set of conditions constrains the variable associated with each loop to live in the one-loop amplituhedron, while the second set of conditions enforces mutual positivity among the different loops. This division provides us with greater control on the source of complexity ‚Äì the mutual positivity. A full understanding of the interplay between these two conditions is still lacking. However, as a starting point we begin by analyzing special configurations which completely trivialize mutual positivity. These cuts are exactly the opposite of the all-loop cuts considered in IntoTheAmplituhedron , which focus on cutting propagators involving external data. Moreover, we begin an investigation of the effects of mutual positivity by introducing this non-triviality in stages.

One way to understand the geometry of the all-loop amplituhedron is by exploring different cuts of the loop integrand. In addition to specifying the structure of the amplituhedron‚Äôs boundaries, these cuts allow us to access all-loop order information about the loop integrand which seems out of reach using any other known method. In this paper, we utilize the reformulation of the amplituhedron outlined in Arkani-Hamed:2017vfh to explore a few faces of the all-loop MHV amplituhedron. These will involve cutting the maximal number of internal propagators involving loop momenta and thus trivializing the mutual positivity conditions between loops. As an example, in terms of Feynman diagrams, at four points, our cut will include (but is not limited to) summing over all diagrams of the form shown in Figure¬†1.

In this sense the cuts we consider in this work probe the contributions of the most complicated multi-loop Feynman diagrams to the loop integrand involving the highest number of internal propagators. We will derive compact expressions for these cuts which are valid at all loop orders and, moreover, for an arbitrary number of external particles. This is a companion paper to Arkani-Hamed:2018caj in which the main results were presented. This paper will explain the results in more detail in addition to presenting other related results.

The paper is structured as follows. In Section¬†2, we will briefly review the amplituhedron and explain the geometry of the different cuts that we analyze in this paper. In Section¬†3, we explore cuts which involve cutting 4‚ÄãL‚àí44ùêø44L{-}4 propagators. We derive expressions for these cuts and verify their correctness against known results. In Section¬†4, we derive the results for 2‚ÄãL‚àí42ùêø42L{-}4 cut propagators which in Arkani-Hamed:2018caj were named the ‚Äúdeepest cuts‚Äù of the amplituhedron. Finally, in Section¬†6, we present a few preliminary results which involve solving nontrivial mutual positivity conditions. We consider the nontrivial deformations away from the deepest cuts, as well as generalized ladder cuts which are nùëõn-point extensions of the four-point results of IntoTheAmplituhedron .

2 Geometry of the Amplituhedron

Although it was initially defined in terms of a generalization of the positive Grassmannian positiveGrass , the amplituhedron can be defined entirely in terms of sign flip conditions on intrinsically four-dimensional data Arkani-Hamed:2017vfh . The external kinematic data for any massless scattering process is completely specified by the (null) external momenta {p1,‚Ä¶,pn}subscriptùëù1‚Ä¶subscriptùëùùëõ\{p_{1},\ldots,p_{n}\} satisfying momentum conservation, and the helicities of the interacting particles. The external momenta can be completely specified by giving nùëõn unconstrained momentum twistors {Z1,‚Ä¶‚ÄãZn}subscriptùëç1‚Ä¶subscriptùëçùëõ\left\{Z_{1},\ldots Z_{n}\right\} as introduced in hodges . In ùí©=4ùí©4\mathcal{N}=4 sYM, it suffices to give the NksuperscriptNùëò\text{N}^{k}MHV degree kùëòk instead of specifying the individual helicities. Additionally, at LùêøL loops the loop integration variables are given by LùêøL lines ‚ÑíŒ±=(A‚ÄãB)Œ±subscript‚Ñíùõºsubscriptùê¥ùêµùõº\mathcal{L}_{\alpha}=(AB)_{\alpha}, Œ±=1,‚Ä¶,Lùõº1‚Ä¶ùêø\alpha=1,\ldots,L, each of which can be specified by two points say, AŒ±subscriptùê¥ùõºA_{\alpha} and BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha}. In terms of these variables, the amplituhedron is the region which satisfies the following conditions:

In this paper, we are interested in some faces of the amplituhedron which trivialize all mutual positivity constraints i.e., we approach the boundary where ‚ü®(A‚ÄãB)Œ±‚Äã(A‚ÄãB)Œ≤‚ü©=0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©subscriptùê¥ùêµùõºsubscriptùê¥ùêµùõΩ0\langle(AB)_{\alpha}(AB)_{\beta}\rangle=0 for all Œ±<Œ≤ùõºùõΩ\alpha<\beta. Generically, this set of constraints has two solutions which are related by parity i.e., the exchange of points‚Üî‚Üî\leftrightarrowplanes. The first solution is a configuration of lines, all of which intersect at a single point Aùê¥A as shown in Figure¬†2. We refer to this solution as the intersecting cut.

It is worthwhile to understand the counting of the number of degrees of freedom left on this boundary. We start with LùêøL loops and hence 4‚ÄãL4ùêø4L degrees of freedom. Making each loop pass through a point requires two constraints. Na√Øvely, this would require 2‚ÄãL2ùêø2L constraints. However, the point at which all the lines intersect is not specified. Hence we only need 2‚ÄãL‚àí32ùêø32L-3 conditions, and the resulting form has degree (2‚ÄãL+3)2ùêø3(2L+3). The remaining conditions on the loop lines are

We seek a cell decomposition of Aùê¥A-space such that for each cell in Aùê¥A space, the geometry of BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} is fixed. To find the canonical form for the configuration in Fig.¬†4, we can find the canonical form associated to the dual inequalities (6) and dualize the form, exchanging Z‚ÜîW‚ÜîùëçùëäZ\leftrightarrow W. Here we are assuming that the dual of the canonical form of the dual region is equal to the canonical form of the original region. We refer the reader to Arkani-Hamed:2017tmz for more details. Similarly, the MHV intersecting cut can be viewed as the dual of the ‚ÄúMHV¬Ø¬ØMHV\overline{\text{MHV}}‚Äù coplanar cut. To keep notation consistent in the rest of this paper we will write all results in terms of the intersection point Aùê¥A, regardless of whether we are considering the intersecting or coplanar cut. Explicit formulae for the two coplanar cuts are obtained by dualizing expressions (4.3) and (81). Before solving these two cuts, however, we will first consider an even simpler set of geometries where the intersecting/coplanar lines satisfy additional constraints.

3 4‚ÄãL‚àí44ùêø44L-4 Cuts of Amplitudes

3.1 Intersecting cut

These are all linear inequalities on the ùêè3superscriptùêè3\mathbf{P}^{3} in which Aùê¥A lives. Therefore they cut out some polytope, provided the inequalities are mutually consistent. To check for the consistency, it suffices to keep track of the sign pattern in the expansion of Aùê¥A in terms of the ZisubscriptùëçùëñZ_{i}. For example, passing through Z1subscriptùëç1Z_{1} forces the pattern to be (?++‚ãØ+)(?++\dots+) or (?‚àí‚àí‚ãØ‚àí)(?--\dots-) and Z2subscriptùëç2Z_{2} forces (‚àí?++‚ãØ+)(-?++\dots+) or (+?‚àí‚àí‚ãØ‚àí)(+?--\dots-), where the ??? means that there are no constraints on the sign of that coefficient. We will now demonstrate this in detail for a few examples.

Let us begin with the the simplest case of n=4ùëõ4n=4 points and two loops. Here we have two lines A‚ÄãB1ùê¥subscriptùêµ1AB_{1} and A‚ÄãB2ùê¥subscriptùêµ2AB_{2}, and we demand that these pass through Z1subscriptùëç1Z_{1} and Z2subscriptùëç2Z_{2}. We can expand

Still working with two loops, we can consider the configuration that results from demanding that the lines pass through Z1subscriptùëç1Z_{1} and Z3subscriptùëç3Z_{3}. The patterns imposed on the cisubscriptùëêùëñc_{i} are (?+++)¬†or¬†(?‚àí‚àí‚àí)(?+++)\text{ or }(?---) from Z1subscriptùëç1Z_{1} and (‚àí‚àí?+)¬†or¬†(++?‚àí)(--?+)\text{ or }(++?-) from Z3subscriptùëç3Z_{3}. To obtain a consistent pattern from these, we would need to make one of the cisubscriptùëêùëñc_{i} vanish. This results in a degenerate configuration and is not allowed for generic loop momenta. Thus there are no consistent patterns and the cut must vanish. We know that this is indeed the case, as shown in TheAmplituhedron . We will also verify this and more general predictions in Section¬†3.2.

While still working at two loops, we can easily generalize the above results to arbitrary nùëõn. If the two lines pass through Z1subscriptùëç1Z_{1} and Z2subscriptùëç2Z_{2}, then, we have

3.2 Verification

In this section, we will verify all predictions made in Section¬†3.1 for two loops. We do this by computing the cuts directly from the two loop MHV integrand which can be expressed in terms of a cylic sum of the double pentagons introduced in Arkani-Hamed:2010gh . We have verified up to n=20ùëõ20n=20 that this prediction holds true in every case. However, the double pentagon expansion provides a triangulation of the two polytopes which is different from (29). Furthermore, there is no obvious subset of terms in the double pentagon form which triangulates either the polytope Conv[Za,‚Ä¶‚ÄãZb]subscriptùëçùëé‚Ä¶subscriptùëçùëè[Z_{a},\dots Z_{b}] or Conv[Zb,‚Ä¶‚ÄãZn,‚àíZ1,‚Ä¶,‚àíZa]subscriptùëçùëè‚Ä¶subscriptùëçùëõsubscriptùëç1‚Ä¶subscriptùëçùëé[Z_{b},\dots Z_{n},-Z_{1},\dots,-Z_{a}] separately. This of course follows from the known fact that the double pentagon expansion of the integrand, although term-by-term local, is not a triangulation in the usual mathematical sense because it involves points living outside the amplituhedron. Understanding exactly how this representation of the integrand covers the amplituhedron, even on this special cut, is an interesting open question which we leave to future work.

3.3 Coplanar cut

In this section we will focus on the coplanar cut of the MHV integrand. Since we are considering coplanar lines, we cannot demand that they pass through the ZisubscriptùëçùëñZ_{i}. This is impossible for generic configurations of external data. However, there exists a natural analog of making the lines A‚ÄãBŒ±ùê¥subscriptùêµùõºAB_{\alpha} pass through ZisubscriptùëçùëñZ_{i}. Consider the planes (i‚àí1‚Äãi‚Äãi+1)ùëñ1ùëñùëñ1(i{-}1ii{+}1), which are dual to the points ZisubscriptùëçùëñZ_{i}. These intersect the plane (A1‚ÄãA2‚ÄãA3)subscriptùê¥1subscriptùê¥2subscriptùê¥3(A_{1}A_{2}A_{3}) in lines as shown in Figure¬†5.

We can identify the lines (A‚ÄãB)Œ±subscriptùê¥ùêµùõº(AB)_{\alpha} with these lines. To understand why this is a natural analog, it is helpful to look at the dual picture. Recall that the dual of a set of coplanar lines is a set of lines intersecting at a point. The dual of a line lying in the plane (i‚àí1‚Äãi‚Äãi+1)ùëñ1ùëñùëñ1(i{-}1ii{+}1) is a line passing through the point ZisubscriptùëçùëñZ_{i}. Thus the dual of the configuration shown in Figure¬†5 is a set of lines intersecting at a point and passing through Zi,ZjsubscriptùëçùëñsubscriptùëçùëóZ_{i},Z_{j} and ZksubscriptùëçùëòZ_{k}. For the rest of this section, we will be working with the dual configuration and demanding the constraints ‚ü®A‚ÄãB‚Äãi‚Äãj‚ü©>0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùêµùëñùëó0\langle ABij\rangle>0 as explained in Section¬†2. We will denote the dual of the common plane A1‚ÄãA2‚ÄãA3subscriptùê¥1subscriptùê¥2subscriptùê¥3A_{1}A_{2}A_{3} by the point Aùê¥A.

The coplanar cut is strikingly different from the intersecting cut. It lacks the rich structure of deeper cuts that we saw in Section¬†3.1. The first result which sets the two cuts apart is that we cannot make A‚ÄãBŒ±ùê¥subscriptùêµùõºAB_{\alpha} pass through non consecutive ZisubscriptùëçùëñZ_{i}. To see this, it suffices to look at the constraints imposed by passing through ZasubscriptùëçùëéZ_{a} and ZbsubscriptùëçùëèZ_{b} for b>aùëèùëéb>a. Let us suppose that passing through aùëéa imposes ‚ü®A‚Äãa‚Äãi‚Äãj‚ü©>0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùëéùëñùëó0\langle Aaij\rangle>0. Passing through b then requires ‚ü®A‚Äãb‚Äãi‚Äãj‚ü©<0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùëèùëñùëó0\langle Abij\rangle<0 since a<bùëéùëèa<b and we must have a consistent sign for ‚ü®A‚Äãa‚Äãb‚Äãj‚ü©delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùëéùëèùëó\langle Aabj\rangle. Now, if there exists cùëêc such that a<c<bùëéùëêùëèa<c<b we have a contradiction, and therefore such a configuration of lines does not belong to the one-loop amplituhedron.

Consequently, configurations of lines passing through three or more of the ZisubscriptùëçùëñZ_{i} are also disallowed since this will necessarily involve two non consecutive ZisubscriptùëçùëñZ_{i}.

4 2‚ÄãL‚àí42ùêø42L-4 Cuts of Amplitudes

We now tackle the problem of finding the form for the cut ‚ü®(A‚ÄãB)Œ±‚Äã(A‚ÄãB)Œ≤‚ü©=0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©subscriptùê¥ùêµùõºsubscriptùê¥ùêµùõΩ0\langle(AB)_{\alpha}(AB)_{\beta}\rangle=0 with no other constraints imposed. As discussed in Arkani-Hamed:2018caj this cut is hopelessly complicated from a local diagram expansion. We can be slightly more quantitative about the complexity of this cut by estimating how many local diagrams contribute at, say, n=4ùëõ4n=4 points using known results available from the soft collinear bootstrap program Bourjaily:2011hi ; Bourjaily:2015bpz ; bourjaily2016 . From the ancillary files in bourjaily2016 the number of dual conformal invariant (DCI) integrals that have enough internal propagators to possibly contribute on the cut can be counted through ten loops, with the number of topologies given in Figure¬†6 which is taken from Arkani-Hamed:2018caj . Note in particular that the total number of diagrams is given by symmetrizing in all loop momenta and cycling through external labels. Of course, simply having enough internal propagators is not sufficient to say that a given diagram actually has support on our cuts, since there may be compensating DCI numerators which cancel some internal propagators and/or kill the residue. Thus, the numbers shown in the ‚Äúpossible contributions‚Äù column of Figure¬†6 are overestimates of the actual contributions, as can be seen by, for example, a more detailed consideration of the thirty-four topologies present at five loops: of these planar graphs twenty have at least the required seven internal propagators necessary to a priori contribute on the cut. However, of these twenty the two graphs shown in Figure¬†7 have the associated DCI numerators

N1=‚àí‚ü®1234‚ü©4‚Äã‚ü®12‚Äã(A‚ÄãB)1‚ü©2‚Äã‚ü®(A‚ÄãB)2‚Äã(A‚ÄãB)3‚ü©2,subscriptùëÅ1superscriptdelimited-‚ü®‚ü©12344superscriptdelimited-‚ü®‚ü©12subscriptùê¥ùêµ12superscriptdelimited-‚ü®‚ü©subscriptùê¥ùêµ2subscriptùê¥ùêµ32N_{1}=-\langle 1234\rangle^{4}\langle 12(AB)_{1}\rangle^{2}\langle(AB)_{2}(AB)_{3}\rangle^{2}, (31)

and

N2=‚àí‚ü®1234‚ü©4‚Äã‚ü®(A‚ÄãB)1‚Äã(A‚ÄãB)2‚ü©4,subscriptùëÅ2superscriptdelimited-‚ü®‚ü©12344superscriptdelimited-‚ü®‚ü©subscriptùê¥ùêµ1subscriptùê¥ùêµ24N_{2}=-\langle 1234\rangle^{4}\langle(AB)_{1}(AB)_{2}\rangle^{4}, (32)

respectively. Therefore neither of these diagrams have nonzero residue on our cut, and the correct counting at five loops is eighteen rather than twenty.

4.2 Five point coplanar cut

At five points we can algebraically solve the inequalities ‚ü®A‚ÄãBŒ±‚Äãi‚Äãj‚ü©>0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥subscriptùêµùõºùëñùëó0\langle AB_{\alpha}ij\rangle>0 by parametrizing Aùê¥A and BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} as above and triangulating the space of allowed common points Aùê¥A for fixed geometries in BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha}. As the number of inequalities to solve becomes large for higher points, this approach becomes computationally intractable.

However, the geometry of the problem is quite simple: we have several intersecting lines with at most quadratic inequalities between them. This suggests that the pieces in the triangulation might in some sense be ‚Äúsimple.‚Äù To see if this is possible we seek an alternative procedure to solve the inequalities which is completely geometric rather than algebraic in nature. In fact, this reformulation of the problem is easy to find: to ‚Äútriangulate‚Äù the space of allowed A‚ÄãBŒ±ùê¥subscriptùêµùõºAB_{\alpha} we should simply draw all configurations of points {Z1,‚Ä¶‚ÄãZn}subscriptùëç1‚Ä¶subscriptùëçùëõ\{Z_{1},\ldots Z_{n}\} allowed by the inequalities ‚ü®A‚ÄãBŒ±‚Äãi‚Äãj‚ü©>0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥subscriptùêµùõºùëñùëó0\langle AB_{\alpha}ij\rangle>0. This is efficiently accomplished by first projecting the external data and the points BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} through the common intersection point Aùê¥A, whence we land on the two dimensional picture of Figure¬†8 where the bracket ‚ü®A‚ÄãB‚Äãi‚Äãj‚ü©delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùêµùëñùëó\langle ABij\rangle is positive if the point BùêµB lies to the right of the line (i‚Äãj)ùëñùëó(ij).

For a given configuration of projected positive external data Z1‚Ä≤,‚Ä¶,Zn‚Ä≤superscriptsubscriptùëç1‚Ä≤‚Ä¶superscriptsubscriptùëçùëõ‚Ä≤Z_{1}^{\prime},\ldots,Z_{n}^{\prime} (henceforth we omit the primes on projected variables) the conditions that A‚ÄãBŒ±ùê¥subscriptùêµùõºAB_{\alpha} is in the one-loop amplituhedron simply demand that the projected point BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} lies to the right of all lines (i‚Äãj)ùëñùëó(ij), for i<jùëñùëói<j. This generates a list of allowed configurations in Aùê¥A along with the corresponding regions in BùêµB from which we can directly write down the forms.

There are eight quadrilateral and eight triangular configurations for the four point case. Checking all possibilities against the inequalities ‚ü®A‚ÄãBŒ±‚Äãi‚Äãj‚ü©>0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥subscriptùêµùõºùëñùëó0\langle AB_{\alpha}ij\rangle>0 for i<j=1,‚Ä¶‚Äã4formulae-sequenceùëñùëó1‚Ä¶4i<j=1,\ldots 4, we find four allowed configurations, displayed in Figure¬†9 as the list of configurations in Aùê¥A and the corresponding regions in BùêµB where the inequalities are satisfied. From these pictures it is trivial to write down the corresponding canonical form, and we find term-by-term agreement with the algebraic approach of the previous section.

To solve the MHV coplanar (although here we are thinking of it as the ‚ÄúMHV¬Ø¬ØMHV\overline{\text{MHV}}‚Äù intersecting) cut at five points, we can proceed by taking the four point configurations just obtained and adding a fifth point everywhere consistent with the additional five point inequalities ‚ü®A‚ÄãB‚Äãi‚Äã5‚ü©>0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùêµùëñ50\langle ABi5\rangle>0, for i=1,‚Ä¶,4ùëñ1‚Ä¶4i=1,\ldots,4. {‚ü®A‚Äã134‚ü©,‚ü®A‚Äã234‚ü©,‚ü®A‚Äã135‚ü©,‚ü®A‚Äã235‚ü©,‚ü®A‚Äã245‚ü©}.delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥134delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥234delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥135delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥235delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥245\{\langle A134\rangle,\langle A234\rangle,\langle A135\rangle,\langle A235\rangle,\langle A245\rangle\}.

The allowed regions in BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} can be classified by the pole structure of the associated form. In the four-point case we found all possible ‚Äútriangles‚Äù with three poles in BùêµB corresponding to the lines (i‚àí1‚Äãi),(i‚Äãi+1)ùëñ1ùëñùëñùëñ1(i{-}1i),(ii{+}1) and (i+1‚Äãi+2)ùëñ1ùëñ2(i{+}1i{+}2), and a priori at nùëõn-points one would anticipate finding triangles, quadrilaterals, etc. up to possibly nùëõn-gons for the allowed regions for BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha}. Indeed, adding a fifth point everywhere in the four-point configurations consistent with the additional five point inequalities yields both quadrilaterals and pentagons in BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha}. However, the corresponding sum of canonical forms for each cell does not reproduce the correct integrand on this cut at any loop order. The reason for this discrepancy is simple: in addition to the inequalities ‚ü®A‚ÄãBŒ±‚Äãi‚Äãj‚ü©>0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥subscriptùêµùõºùëñùëó0\langle AB_{\alpha}ij\rangle>0 we must ensure that we are only keeping configurations that are consistent with having been projected from positive data. To be more explicit, consider the following five-point configuration obtained from the procedure outlined above which is consistent with the inequalities ‚ü®A‚ÄãBŒ±‚Äãi‚Äãj‚ü©>0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥subscriptùêµùõºùëñùëó0\langle AB_{\alpha}ij\rangle>0 (here the point Z3subscriptùëç3Z_{3} must lie to the right of the line (14)14(14) and to the left of the line (25)25(25) to give the region in BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} shown)

(39)

Na√Øvely this configuration contributes to the cut with a quadrilateral region for BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} with poles ‚ü®A‚ÄãB‚Äã12‚ü©,‚ü®A‚ÄãB‚Äã34‚ü©,‚ü®A‚ÄãB‚Äã45‚ü©delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùêµ12delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùêµ34delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùêµ45\langle AB12\rangle,\langle AB34\rangle,\langle AB45\rangle and ‚ü®A‚ÄãB‚Äã15‚ü©delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùêµ15\langle AB15\rangle. However, this configuration of projected ZisubscriptùëçùëñZ_{i} is actually inconsistent with having been projected from positive data, as a simple argument demonstrates. Namely, if we expand Z5subscriptùëç5Z_{5} in the basis Z1,‚Ä¶,Z4subscriptùëç1‚Ä¶subscriptùëç4Z_{1},\ldots,Z_{4} we have

which is in contradiction to the configuration we have drawn, where ‚ü®A‚Äã135‚ü©>0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥1350\langle A135\rangle>0. Thus, the configuration (39) cannot be obtained by the projection of positive data.

If we cross-check the list of configurations obtained by adding a fifth point to the allowed four-point cases of Figure¬†9 against the positivity constraints on the external data, the surprising result is the elimination of all geometries apart from triangles in BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha}. The complete set of configurations can be constructed out of the following list:

In these results, we have indicated the regions in BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} satisfying the one-loop inequalities by the codimension one boundaries which are lines (i‚Äãi+1)ùëñùëñ1(ii{+}1) in the projection through Aùê¥A. The full set of allowed configurations is given by adding all reflections across the line (12)12(12) of the above list (disregarding duplicates), which is equivalent to requiring the consideration of both cases ‚ü®A‚Äã123‚ü©‚â∑0greater-than-or-less-thandelimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥1230\langle A123\rangle\gtrless 0. Alternatively, all possibilities can be generated by constructing, for each possible BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} region, all configurations consistent with the inequalities (with no requirements on any ‚ü®A‚Äãi‚Äãj‚Äãk‚ü©delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùëñùëóùëò\langle Aijk\rangle bracket); this leads to exactly the same set of allowed configurations as (42)-(51), plus reflections across (12)12(12).

As already mentioned, the key aspect of the five point results (42)-(51) is that only triangles in BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} are found, despite there being no immediately obvious reason why quadrilaterals and pentagons are forbidden. In fact, if one repeats the above brute-force procedure to construct the complete set of six point geometries, the same simple result is found: only triangles in BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} satisfy the inequalities and are consistent with the positivity of external data. Although a deep explanation of why the positivity constraints demand triangle geometry for the BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} is at this point missing, in Appendix¬†A we discuss the precise nature of the constraints imposed on the projected data in slightly more detail. However, even without a satisfying explanation for this simplicity, we can immediately make an obvious ansatz: namely, for an arbitrary number of particles, the geometry in BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} is still no more complicated than triangles! As we will see below this powerful hypothesis, checked by brute force at five and six points, allows use to solve the problem completely for any nùëõn by a simple unitarity-inspired procedure. Since we know the allowed regions for the BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha}, we can obtain the corresponding Œ©AsubscriptŒ©ùê¥\Omega_{A} from the known two loop MHV integrands (15) by taking residues. At higher points our triangle-hypothesis has been verified by matching our prediction for the cut against known expressions for the full integrand.

4.3 Coplanar cut for arbitrary multiplicities

It was shown in Section¬†3.3 that the coplanar cut allowed only a limited number of deeper cuts. In particular, we cannot have any Œ©BsubscriptŒ©ùêµ\Omega_{B} which allows passing through more than two ZisubscriptùëçùëñZ_{i}. We allow for all possible Œ©BsubscriptŒ©ùêµ\Omega_{B} with three factors of ‚ü®A‚ÄãB‚Äãi‚Äãi+1‚ü©delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùêµùëñùëñ1\langle ABii+1\rangle in the denominator and determine the corresponding Œ©AsubscriptŒ©ùê¥\Omega_{A}. Surprisingly, this turns out to be the exact form on the cut for arbitrary nùëõn and LùêøL. There can be three kinds of Œ©BsubscriptŒ©ùêµ\Omega_{B} with the following factors in the denominator.

4.4 Verification of Œ©n(L)superscriptsubscriptŒ©ùëõùêø\Omega_{n}^{(L)}

We have verified that the expression for Œ©n(L)superscriptsubscriptŒ©ùëõùêø\Omega_{n}^{(L)} matches the coplanar cut of the two-loop MHV integrand up to n=20ùëõ20n=20. We also verified that Œ©n(L)superscriptsubscriptŒ©ùëõùêø\Omega_{n}^{(L)} reproduces the cut of the three-loop MHV integrand given in Arkani-Hamed:2010gh up to (and including) n=7ùëõ7n=7.

4.5 Intersecting cut

4.5.1 Five points

We now consider the MHV intersecting cut where all lines intersect in a common point Aùê¥A. Na√Øvely, one might hope that the simplicity of (4.3) is mirrored in this cut as well. However, the lack of complexity in the coplanar cut arose from the fact that the only allowed regions in the BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} were triangles. This is clearly impossible for the intersecting cut due to the results of Section¬†3.1 which show non-vanishing residues for the intersecting lines (A‚ÄãB)Œ±subscriptùê¥ùêµùõº(AB)_{\alpha} passing through any number of external points. It is also straightforward to verify that, for example, the three-loop five point integrand has a non-vanishing residue on the cut where B1=Z2subscriptùêµ1subscriptùëç2B_{1}=Z_{2} and B2=Z4subscriptùêµ2subscriptùëç4B_{2}=Z_{4} which no triangle in BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} can possibly reproduce. Instead, at five points we make the following ansatz:

4.5.2 Six points

At six points it can be verified that on the cut B1=Z2,B2=Z4,B3=Z5formulae-sequencesubscriptùêµ1subscriptùëç2formulae-sequencesubscriptùêµ2subscriptùëç4subscriptùêµ3subscriptùëç5B_{1}=Z_{2},B_{2}=Z_{4},B_{3}=Z_{5} the three-loop integrand has nonzero residue. 4.6 Verification of intersecting cut

The result (81) has been checked against the expressions for the two- and three-loop MHV integrands given in Arkani-Hamed:2010gh through n=10ùëõ10n=10 points.

5 Coplanar - intersecting cuts and path dependence

An obvious degeneration of the above configurations would be to demand that all the lines lie in a plane and intersect each other. Here, we will see that the order in which the limit is taken determines the result. Recall that the form in (4.3) is actually the form of the dual configuration in which all the dual lines are intersecting and we demand that they satisfy ‚ü®A‚ÄãBŒ±‚Äãi‚Äãj‚ü©>0,‚àÄi,jdelimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥subscriptùêµùõºùëñùëó0for-allùëñùëó\langle AB_{\alpha}ij\rangle>0,\forall i,j. We can now take the limit ‚ü®A‚Äã123‚ü©=‚ü®A‚ÄãBŒ±‚Äã12‚ü©=0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥123delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥subscriptùêµùõº120\langle A123\rangle=\langle AB_{\alpha}12\rangle=0 or ‚ü®A‚Äã123‚ü©=‚ü®A‚ÄãBŒ±‚Äã23‚ü©=0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥123delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥subscriptùêµùõº230\langle A123\rangle=\langle AB_{\alpha}23\rangle=0 which forces all the lines A‚ÄãBŒ±ùê¥subscriptùêµùõºAB_{\alpha} (which already intersect at Aùê¥A) to lie in the common plane (123)123(123). We can perform a similar procedure on the form in (81)81(\ref{eq:intersectingCut}). We will show below that the results are significantly different.

First consider the intersecting cut. To make the configuration collapse to the plane (123)123(123), we need a pole ‚ü®A‚Äã123‚ü©delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥123\langle A123\rangle in addition to either ‚ü®A‚ÄãBŒ±‚Äã12‚ü©delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥subscriptùêµùõº12\langle AB_{\alpha}12\rangle or ‚ü®A‚ÄãBŒ±‚Äã23‚ü©delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥subscriptùêµùõº23\langle AB_{\alpha}23\rangle. Note that there are two solutions to ‚ü®A‚ÄãBŒ±‚Äã12‚ü©=‚ü®A‚ÄãBŒ±‚Äã23‚ü©=0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥subscriptùêµùõº12delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥subscriptùêµùõº230\langle AB_{\alpha}12\rangle=\langle AB_{\alpha}23\rangle=0, one in which (A‚ÄãBŒ±)ùê¥subscriptùêµùõº(AB_{\alpha}) passes through Z2subscriptùëç2Z_{2} and the other in which it lies in the plane (123)123(123). However, since all the regions in BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} are polygons, they are designed to have singularities only on their vertices. Thus the numerator is designed to kill the singularity in which the line lies in the plane (123)123(123). This is precisely the singularity we are looking for. Hence we can achieve this limit only if the pole ‚ü®A‚Äã123‚ü©delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥123\langle A123\rangle is present, which severely restricts the number of terms that can contribute to this cut. In fact, it is easy to see that only the triangles can contribute. Thus, we are left with the result that at LùêøL loops and nùëõn, points, if Aùê¥A lies in the plane (123)123(123), the corresponding region in BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} must be either the triangle (12)‚Äã(23)‚Äã(34)122334(12)(23)(34) or (n‚Äã1)‚Äã(12)‚Äã(23)ùëõ11223(n1)(12)(23).

We can derive the same result directly from the amplituhedron. Since we are interested in a configuration of coincident, coplanar lines in the MHV amplituhedron, we can parametrize them as follows

A=Z1+a2‚ÄãZ2+a3‚ÄãZ3ùê¥subscriptùëç1subscriptùëé2subscriptùëç2subscriptùëé3subscriptùëç3\displaystyle A=Z_{1}+a_{2}Z_{2}+a_{3}Z_{3}
BŒ±=Z1+bŒ±‚ÄãZ2subscriptùêµùõºsubscriptùëç1subscriptùëèùõºsubscriptùëç2\displaystyle B_{\alpha}=Z_{1}+b_{\alpha}Z_{2}

and demand ‚ü®A‚ÄãB‚Äãi¬Ø‚Äãj¬Ø‚ü©>0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùêµ¬Øùëñ¬Øùëó0\langle AB\bar{i}\bar{j}\rangle>0. The mutual positivity is trivialized and the form is just the product of the form for each BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha}. It is not hard to see that the final result is

Œ©c‚Äãc=1a2‚Äãa3‚Äã(‚àèŒ±=1L1(a2‚àíbŒ±)+‚àèŒ±=1L1bŒ±).superscriptŒ©ùëêùëê1subscriptùëé2subscriptùëé3superscriptsubscriptproductùõº1ùêø1subscriptùëé2subscriptùëèùõºsuperscriptsubscriptproductùõº1ùêø1subscriptùëèùõº\displaystyle\Omega^{cc}=\frac{1}{a_{2}a_{3}}\left(\prod_{\alpha=1}^{L}\frac{1}{(a_{2}-b_{\alpha})}+\prod_{\alpha=1}^{L}\frac{1}{b_{\alpha}}\right). (82)

The first term corresponds to the triangle (n‚Äã1)‚Äã(12)‚Äã(23)ùëõ11223(n1)(12)(23) and the second to (12)‚Äã(23)‚Äã(34)122334(12)(23)(34).

In contrast with this simple result, the coplanar cut yields a far more complex residue. Indeed whenever BŒ±subscriptùêµùõºB_{\alpha} is in any triangle whose edge is either (12)12(12) or (23)23(23), the corresponding region in Aùê¥A has the pole ‚ü®A‚Äã123‚ü©delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥123\langle A123\rangle required to collapse the configuration into the (123)123(123) plane.

6 Moving beyond trivial mutual positivity

The results in equations (4.3), (81) and (82) are valid for an arbitrary number of loops. While analytic all-loop results are few and far between, it is essential to realize that it was possible to obtain these results only because of the trivial mutual positivity condition. It is essentially equivalent to solving a one-loop problem. In this section, we begin exploring a few different configurations in which the mutual positivity conditions are not completely trivialized. We see that the associated geometries are far richer and the corresponding canonical forms more complex. In Section¬†6.1, we consider generalized ladder cuts where we cut only external propagators, while in Section¬†6.2 we examine several cuts which are directly related to the intersecting and coplanar cuts.

6.1 Ladder cuts

Moving to three loops, for the set {i1,i2,i3}subscriptùëñ1subscriptùëñ2subscriptùëñ3\{i_{1},i_{2},i_{3}\} there are three possibilities: (i) all three indices are distinct, (ii) Two of the indices are equal, or (iii) all three indices are equal. 6.2 Extra free lines

In this section, we will consider a series of cuts in which the configuration of lines (A‚ÄãB)Œ±subscriptùê¥ùêµùõº(AB)_{\alpha} are minor modifications to the coplanar and collinear cut. In each case, we consider an extra line which allows for non trivial mutual positivity. In order of increasing difficulty, some of the types of cuts we consider involve the following configurations of lines:

  • ‚Ä¢

    Cut 1: L‚àí1ùêø1L{-}1 loops intersecting in a common point Aùê¥A, with each line passing through one of the external ZisubscriptùëçùëñZ_{i}. We can denote these lines as A‚Äãiùê¥ùëñAi. An additional line passes through some ZjsubscriptùëçùëóZ_{j}, but does not intersect the lines A‚Äãiùê¥ùëñAi in Aùê¥A. Denoting this line by B‚ÄãjùêµùëóBj, the non trivial mutual positivity conditions are ‚ü®A‚Äãi‚ÄãB‚Äãj‚ü©>0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥ùëñùêµùëó0\langle AiBj\rangle>0.

  • ‚Ä¢

    Cut 2: L‚àí1ùêø1L{-}1 loops A‚Äãiùê¥ùëñAi, intersecting in a common point Aùê¥A and passing through some ZisubscriptùëçùëñZ_{i} with the LthsuperscriptùêøthL^{\text{th}} line C‚ÄãDùê∂ùê∑CD completely free.   • ‚Ä¢

    Cut 3: L‚àí1ùêø1L{-}1 loops A‚ÄãBŒ±ùê¥subscriptùêµùõºAB_{\alpha} which intersect at Aùê¥A with the LthsuperscriptùêøthL^{\text{th}} line C‚ÄãDùê∂ùê∑CD intersecting two of the lines A‚ÄãBiùê¥subscriptùêµùëñAB_{i} and A‚ÄãBjùê¥subscriptùêµùëóAB_{j} resulting in the non trivial constraint ‚ü®A‚ÄãBŒ±‚ÄãC‚ÄãD‚ü©>0delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùê¥subscriptùêµùõºùê∂ùê∑0\langle AB_{\alpha}CD\rangle>0 with Œ±‚â†i,jùõºùëñùëó\alpha\neq i,j.

    Cut 4: L‚àí1ùêø1L{-}1 loops intersecting in a common point Aùê¥A with the LthsuperscriptùêøthL^{\text{th}} line completely free. This is a generalization of the above cut.

The first two cuts are generalizations of the (4‚ÄãL‚àí4)4ùêø4(4L{-}4)-cuts of Section¬†3.1 while the next two are related to the (2‚ÄãL‚àí4)2ùêø4(2L{-}4) cuts of Section¬†4.

Cut 1:
Here, the configuration of lines A‚Äãiùê¥ùëñAi is the same as in Section 3.1, with modifications for the LthsuperscriptùêøthL^{\text{th}} loop as shown in Figure¬†15.

We begin by solving this problem at four and five points to illustrate the complications presented by mutual positivity.

A generic configuration at four points includes L1subscriptùêø1L_{1} lines passing through Z1subscriptùëç1Z_{1}, L2subscriptùêø2L_{2} lines passing through Z2subscriptùëç2Z_{2}, L3subscriptùêø3L_{3} through Z3subscriptùëç3Z_{3} and L4subscriptùêø4L_{4} through Z4subscriptùëç4Z_{4}. This cut has already computed in IntoTheAmplituhedron using a slightly different approach. where the numerator N‚Äã(A‚ÄãBŒ±,B1‚ÄãB2)ùëÅùê¥subscriptùêµùõºsubscriptùêµ1subscriptùêµ2N\left(AB_{\alpha},B_{1}B_{2}\right) is a sum with several hundred terms. We have verified the result of this calculation matches the full four-point four-loop integrand, which is a sum of eight local diagrams, symmetrized over all loop momenta and cyclically summed over external legs and given explicitly in momentum twistor variables in ArkaniHamed2015 , evaluated on this cut.

The same cut at five points is also solvable with the amplituhedron, although we have yet to find a particularly simple representation of the canonical form which suggests a generalization to higher points and loops. We plan to revisit these problems as well as generalized corner cuts in future work.

7 Conclusion

The all-loop amplituhedron is a remarkable mathematical object capturing the complicated loop-level structure of scattering amplitudes in planar ùí©=4ùí©4\mathcal{N}=4 sYM in geometric form directly in the physical kinematic space. This paper has been concerned with the practical application of this geometric picture to make predictions about the MHV loop integrand, valid for any number of particles and any number of loops, which are completely hidden in the usual unitarity or recursion-based methods. In particular we studied a series of cuts which probed the part of the loop-integrand which is, in the Feynman diagram expansion, encoded in the subset of diagrams with many internal propagators which have complicated branch-cut structure. We found remarkably simple expressions for the canonical forms for these ‚Äúmaximally intersecting‚Äù cuts. The topological winding formulation of the amplituhedron of¬†Arkani-Hamed:2017tmz was crucial in deriving our results. In fact without this sign flip picture even a qualitative description of the canonical forms (81) and (4.3), the central results of this paper, would likely be impossible. However, from the perspective of the amplituhedron, the factorization of the canonical forms on the intersecting and coplanar cuts is completely trivial and follows directly from the definition of the geometry. However, our analysis reveals an even greater simplicity than one would na√Øvely guess: for the intersecting cut the allowable space for the intersection point is naturally triangulated by a simple collection of tetrahedra, while the remaining degrees of freedom of the loop lines live inside a polygon.

This work is a continuation of a systematic exploration of the facets of the amplituhedron for all n,k,Lùëõùëòùêøn,k,L. As such, there are a number of avenues for further investigation: first, there are the unfinished cuts presented in Section¬†6.2 which gradually relax some of the constraints imposed on the maximally intersecting cuts we solved. The most interesting (and complicated) extension of the all-loop results presented here involve L‚àí1ùêø1L{-}1 lines intersecting in a common point Aùê¥A with the LthsuperscriptùêøthL^{\text{th}} line free; solving this cut would amount to a complete understanding of the MHV two-loop geometry. Although the direct product form of the solutions obtained to all-loop orders will of course not remain, preliminary considerations suggest that simple geometrical decompositions of the canonical forms do persist to these more generic cuts. Another natural starting point for further work is to consider the same maximally intersecting cuts for k‚â•1ùëò1k\geq 1 i.e., different helicity sectors. For example, by parity conjugation the NMHV five-point coplanar cut is simply the RùëÖR-invariant [12345]delimited-[]12345[12345] multiplying the result derived in this paper at five points. In the general n,kùëõùëòn,k case although the product form will remain, the sign flip conditions change for both the external data and the loop momentum variables; however, it is likely that just as in the MHV configuration considered here, these problems will ultimately reduce to finding the right way of understanding the corresponding one-loop geometries for arbitrary n,kùëõùëòn,k. Finally, there is another class of facets of the amplituhedron which are of physical interest. These involve unitarity cuts which trivialize the inequalities involving external data while leaving the mutual positivity conditions untouched. An example of these are the ‚Äúcorner cuts‚Äù computed in¬†IntoTheAmplituhedron at four points where loop lines pass through either ZisubscriptùëçùëñZ_{i} or (i‚àí1‚Äãi‚Äãi+1)ùëñ1ùëñùëñ1(i{-}1ii{+}1). A detailed understanding of such corner cuts, along with complete knowledge of the structure of the integrand on the maximally intersecting cuts initiated here, would be invaluable to the goal of reconstructing the full loop integrand directly from the amplituhedron.

Appendix A Constraints from projecting positive data

In this appendix, we derive the constraints that result from projecting positive data. We derive the constraints that must be satisfied by 3 dimensional data which are the result of projecting four dimensional positive data. Let us start with n=5ùëõ5n=5. We can add one extra component and turn them into 4D data.

Theorem 1

Exactly one of the following systems has a solution.
(1) yT‚ÄãA>0superscriptùë¶ùëáùê¥0y^{T}A>0 for some y‚ààùêënùë¶superscriptùêëùëõy\in\mathbf{R}^{n}
(2) A‚Äãx=0,x‚â•0formulae-sequenceùê¥ùë•0ùë•0Ax=0,x\geq 0 for some non zero x‚ààùêënùë•superscriptùêëùëõx\in\mathbf{R}^{n}

We can easily see that any vector of the form (‚ü®ùüì‚Äãùêö‚Äãùêõ‚ü©‚àí‚ü®ùüí‚Äãùêö‚Äãùêõ‚ü©‚ü®ùüë‚Äãùêö‚Äãùêõ‚ü©‚àí‚ü®ùüê‚Äãùêö‚Äãùêõ‚ü©‚ü®ùüè‚Äãùêö‚Äãùêõ‚ü©)matrixdelimited-‚ü®‚ü©5ùêöùêõmissing-subexpressiondelimited-‚ü®‚ü©4ùêöùêõmissing-subexpressiondelimited-‚ü®‚ü©3ùêöùêõmissing-subexpressiondelimited-‚ü®‚ü©2ùêöùêõmissing-subexpressiondelimited-‚ü®‚ü©1ùêöùêõ\begin{pmatrix}\langle{\bf 5ab}\rangle&&-\langle{\bf 4ab}\rangle&&\langle{\bf 3ab}\rangle&&-\langle{\bf 2ab}\rangle&&\langle{\bf 1ab}\rangle\end{pmatrix} is a null eigenvector as a consequence of the Schouten identity. Here ùêöùêö{\bf a} and ùêõùêõ{\bf b} are any two 3D vectors. From Gordan‚Äôs theorem, the condition for the existence of a solution and consequently the constraint on the 3D data is that not all entries of the null vector are positive. Let us choose ùêö=ùê≥1ùêösubscriptùê≥1{\bf a}={\bf z}_{1} and ùêõ=ùê≥2ùêõsubscriptùê≥2{\bf b}={\bf z}_{2}. However, in this case we cannot say anything about the sign flips of the sequences resulting from a different choice of ùêöùêö{\bf a} and ùêõùêõ{\bf b}. Furthermore, any one of them having the wrong flip pattern is sufficient to show that this 3D data cannot arise from positive 4D data.

This can be easily extended beyond n=5ùëõ5n=5. At an arbitrary nùëõn, we have to impose positivity of all ordered minors ‚ü®i‚Äãj‚Äãk‚Äãl‚ü©delimited-‚ü®‚ü©ùëñùëóùëòùëô\langle ijkl\rangle with i<j<k<lùëñùëóùëòùëôi<j<k<l.
